# Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition of a Queue

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **QUEUE (Linear Data Structure)**: A queue is an ordered collection of homogeneous elements in which the **insertion (enqueue)** operation is performed at one end called the **REAR**, and the **deletion (dequeue)** operation is performed at the other end called the **FRONT**. It strictly follows the **FIFO (First-In, First-Out)** principle, also known as the **FCFS (First-Come, First-Served)** discipline.

In the context of the KTU 2024 syllabus for *Data Structures Lab*, a queue is treated as an **abstract data type (ADT)** with a well-defined set of operations and access restrictions — only the front element can be removed, and new elements are always appended at the rear.

### Conceptual Analogy / Real-World Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Analogy — The Cinema Ticket Counter**
> Imagine a single line of people standing in front of a ticket counter at a cinema hall. The person who **arrived first** (at the front of the line) gets the **ticket first** and **leaves the line first**. New customers always **join at the back (rear)** of the line. This perfectly models the FIFO behavior of a queue. No one in the middle of the line is served — strict order is preserved.

## 1.2 Formal Definition of a Circular Queue

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **CIRCULAR QUEUE**: A circular queue is a variant of the linear queue in which the last position is logically connected back to the first position, forming a **circular ring**. This connection is achieved through **modular arithmetic** on the `rear` and `front` indices, allowing **efficient utilization of the array space** and preventing the wasteful "false overflow" condition that occurs in a linear queue.

### Conceptual Analogy / Real-World Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Analogy — The Circular Train Turntable / Clock Face**
> Picture the hour markings on a **clock face**. After **12**, the next hour is **1** — the counting wraps around. Similarly, in a circular queue of size `N`, an index of `N` is logically equivalent to index `0`. This is exactly how the `rear` and `front` indices behave — they "loop back" using the modulo operator.

## 1.3 Standard Metrics & Terminology

| Term | Meaning |
|---|---|
| **Size (MAX)** | **Total capacity** of the underlying array (constant). |
| **Front** | Index of the element currently at the front of the queue (where deletion happens). |
| **Rear** | Index of the last inserted element (where the next insertion will occur). |
| **Empty Queue** | A queue with **zero elements** — initial state. |
| **Overflow** | Condition when `rear == MAX - 1` (linear) or `(rear + 1) % MAX == front` (circular). |
| **Underflow** | Condition when an attempt is made to delete from an **empty queue**. |

