# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Queue ADT — The Core Operations

The queue ADT supports the following fundamental operations. Each operation must be analyzed for its **time complexity**, as this is a frequent viva question in KTU lab examinations.

> [!NOTE]
> **Core 'Why' Behind Queue Operations**: A queue is fundamentally a **restricted linear list**. The restriction that insertions happen only at `rear` and deletions only at `front` is what gives it the FIFO property. All operations on a **well-implemented array-based queue** must run in **O(1)** time — meaning they must NOT depend on the size of the queue.

### Operation Set

1. **Enqueue (Insertion)** — Add an element to the `rear` end.
2. **Dequeue (Deletion)** — Remove and return the element from the `front` end.
3. **Peek / Front** — Return the front element without removing it.
4. **isEmpty** — Check whether the queue has zero elements.
5. **isFull** — Check whether the queue has reached its capacity.
6. **Display** — Traverse and print all elements.

## 2.2 The Linear Queue — Operational Logic

### Initialization State

When a linear queue is initialized:
- `front = -1`
- `rear = -1`

This is the **empty state** sentinel.

### Enqueue Operation (Step-by-Step Logic)

1. **Check for Overflow**: If `rear == MAX - 1`, print "Queue Overflow" and **return**.
2. **First-element special case**: If `front == -1`, set `front = 0`.
3. **Increment rear**: `rear = rear + 1`.
4. **Insert element**: `queue[rear] = item`.

### Dequeue Operation (Step-by-Step Logic)

1. **Check for Underflow**: If `front == -1` **OR** `front > rear`, print "Queue Underflow" and **return**.
2. **Retrieve element**: `item = queue[front]`.
3. **Increment front**: `front = front + 1`.
4. **Reset if empty after deletion**: If `front > rear`, reset both `front = -1` and `rear = -1`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The "False Overflow" Problem in Linear Queue**
> Consider a queue of size 5. After 5 insertions and 2 deletions, `rear = 4` and `front = 2`. Three slots (`0`, `1`) at the **front** are now vacant, but the linear queue reports **OVERFLOW** because `rear == MAX - 1`. New elements cannot be inserted even though space exists! This is the **false overflow** or **"memory wastage"** problem that the circular queue solves.

## 2.3 The Circular Queue — Operational Logic

The circular queue reuses the freed front slots by wrapping indices around using **modulo arithmetic** with the queue capacity `MAX`.

### Initialization State

- `front = -1`
- `rear = -1`

### The Modular Wrap-Around Rule

$$\text{next\_index} = (current\_index + 1) \bmod MAX$$

This single equation is the **heart** of every circular queue implementation.

### Enqueue Operation (Step-by-Step Logic)

1. **Check for Overflow**: If `((rear + 1) \bmod MAX) == front`, print "Queue Overflow" and **return**.
2. **First-element special case**: If `front == -1`, set `front = 0`.
3. **Increment rear (with wrap)**: `rear = (rear + 1) \bmod MAX`.
4. **Insert element**: `queue[rear] = item`.

### Dequeue Operation (Step-by-Step Logic)

1. **Check for Underflow**: If `front == -1`, print "Queue Underflow" and **return**.
2. **Retrieve element**: `item = queue[front]`.
3. **Single-element special case**: If `front == rear`, reset both to `-1`.
4. **Increment front (with wrap)**: `front = (front + 1) \bmod MAX`.

## 2.4 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| # | Concept | Formula / Condition | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Next index (wrap) | $\text{next} = (i + 1) \bmod N$ | Core of circular queue |
| 2 | Empty (circular) | $\text{front} = -1$ | Sentinel value |
| 3 | Full (circular) | $(rear + 1) \bmod N = front$ | One slot is always sacrificed |
| 4 | Full (linear) | $\text{rear} = N - 1$ | Cannot recover freed slots |
| 5 | Empty (linear) | $\text{front} = -1$ or $\text{front} > \text{rear}$ | Post-deletion reset needed |
| 6 | Element count (circular) | $(N - \text{front} + \text{rear} + 1) \bmod N$ | When `front != -1` |
| 7 | Time — enqueue | $O(1)$ | Constant-time insertion |
| 8 | Time — dequeue | $O(1)$ | Constant-time deletion |
| 9 | Space complexity | $O(N)$ | Array of size `MAX` |
| 10 | Worst-case slots wasted | **1 slot** (circular) | Trade-off for empty/full distinction |

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

> [!NOTE]
> **Where are these used?**
> - **Operating Systems**: CPU scheduling algorithms like **Round Robin** rely on a circular queue.
> - **Memory Management**: Circular buffers are used in **DMA transfers**, **audio/video streaming**, and **kernel ring buffers**.
> - **Networking**: Packet scheduling in routers.
> - **Disk Drives**: Request buffering uses circular queues.

---

