# Section 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Derivation — Why Modulo Arithmetic is Used in Circular Queues

### Problem Setup

Suppose we have a circular queue of capacity **N = 5**, currently in the state where:
- `rear = 4` (last valid index of the array)
- The user now wants to **enqueue** another element.

### Step-by-Step Derivation

In a linear queue, `rear = 4` would immediately trigger an **overflow** condition, even if slot `0` is free. We need a formula that allows `rear` to "wrap" from `4` back to `0`.

We require a function $f$ such that:
$$f(\text{rear}) = (rear + 1) \bmod N$$

**For rear = 4 and N = 5:**

$$\begin{aligned}
f(4) &= (4 + 1) \bmod 5 \\
&= 5 \bmod 5 \\
&= 0
\end{aligned}$$

**Logic explained**: $5 \bmod 5 = 0$ because 5 divided by 5 leaves a remainder of **0**. So the new `rear` is **0** — the slot that was freed after a `dequeue` earlier. This confirms that the formula correctly reuses the freed slot.

### Verification With Multiple Cases

**Case 1 — Normal increment (no wrap needed):**

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= 1, \quad N = 5 \\
f(1) &= (1 + 1) \bmod 5 \\
&= 2 \bmod 5 \\
&= 2
\end{aligned}$$

**Case 2 — Exact boundary (wrap triggers):**

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= 4, \quad N = 5 \\
f(4) &= (4 + 1) \bmod 5 \\
&= 5 \bmod 5 \\
&= 0
\end{aligned}$$

**Case 3 — Two wraps (after another insert + delete):**

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= 3, \quad N = 5 \\
f(3) &= (3 + 1) \bmod 5 \\
&= 4 \bmod 5 \\
&= 4
\end{aligned}$$

All three cases yield correct indices, confirming the modular arithmetic is valid in every scenario.

## 3.2 Derivation — The "One Slot Sacrificed" Trade-off

### Problem Setup

We need a single condition that **uniquely distinguishes** between an *empty* queue and a *full* queue in a circular queue. Since both `front` and `rear` cycle through `0` to `N-1`, the condition `front == rear` is ambiguous — it could mean *both empty and both full*.

### Step-by-Step Derivation

**Option considered**: Use an additional `count` variable.

**Alternative chosen** (more memory-efficient): **Sacrifice one slot**. When the queue is full, we force the condition:

$$(\text{rear} + 1) \bmod N = \text{front}$$

This means `rear` is always **one position behind** `front` when full.

**Capacity verification for N = 5:**

- **Maximum usable slots** = `N - 1` = **4**
- **Sacrificed slot** = 1 (always kept empty)

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Usable Capacity} &= N - 1 \\
&= 5 - 1 \\
&= 4 \text{ elements}
\end{aligned}$$

### Justification Table

| State | front | rear (for N=5) | Verification |
|---|---|---|---|
| Empty | -1 | -1 | `front == -1` triggers empty check |
| 1 element | 0 | 0 | rear wraps back to 0 |
| 4 elements (full) | 0 | 3 | $(3+1) \bmod 5 = 4 \neq 0$, so not full yet... wait, $(3+1)\%5=4$ ≠ `front=0`. To make full, we need **rear=4**: $(4+1)\%5 = 0$ == `front=0` ✓ |
| After dequeue | 1 | 4 | $(4+1)\%5 = 0$ ≠ `front=1`, so not full — slot `0` is now usable again |

## 3.3 State Transition Trace — Worked Example

> [!NOTE]
> **Worked Example**: Circular queue with `MAX = 5`. Trace through: Enqueue 10, 20, 30, Dequeue, Enqueue 40, 50, 60.

### Initial State

$$\text{front} = -1, \quad \text{rear} = -1$$

### Operation 1: Enqueue 10

`front == -1`, so set `front = 0`.

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= (-1 + 1) \bmod 5 = 0 \\
\text{queue}[\text{rear}] &= \text{queue}[0] = 10
\end{aligned}$$

State: `front = 0, rear = 0`. Queue: `[10, _, _, _, _]`

### Operation 2: Enqueue 20

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= (0 + 1) \bmod 5 = 1 \\
\text{queue}[1] &= 20
\end{aligned}$$

State: `front = 0, rear = 1`. Queue: `[10, 20, _, _, _]`

### Operation 3: Enqueue 30

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= (1 + 1) \bmod 5 = 2 \\
\text{queue}[2] &= 30
\end{aligned}$$

State: `front = 0, rear = 2`. Queue: `[10, 20, 30, _, _]`

### Operation 4: Dequeue

Retrieve `queue[0] = 10`.

$$\text{front} = (0 + 1) \bmod 5 = 1$$

State: `front = 1, rear = 2`. Queue: `[_, 20, 30, _, _]`

### Operation 5: Enqueue 40

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= (2 + 1) \bmod 5 = 3 \\
\text{queue}[3] &= 40
\end{aligned}$$

State: `front = 1, rear = 3`. Queue: `[_, 20, 30, 40, _]`

### Operation 6: Enqueue 50

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= (3 + 1) \bmod 5 = 4 \\
\text{queue}[4] &= 50
\end{aligned}$$

State: `front = 1, rear = 4`. Queue: `[_, 20, 30, 40, 50]`

### Operation 7: Enqueue 60 — The Wrap

Check overflow: $(4 + 1) \bmod 5 = 0$. `front = 1`. `0 ≠ 1` → **NOT full**, proceed.

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{rear} &= (4 + 1) \bmod 5 = 0 \\
\text{queue}[0] &= 60
\end{aligned}$$

State: `front = 1, rear = 0`. Queue: `[60, 20, 30, 40, 50]`

### Operation 8: Enqueue 70 — Should Overflow

Check overflow: $(0 + 1) \bmod 5 = 1$. `front = 1`. `1 == 1` → **OVERFLOW** ✓

This trace conclusively demonstrates that the circular queue correctly handles the wrap-around and the overflow condition.

---

<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

