# Section 4: Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Linear Queue — Block-Level Functional Architecture

The following diagram maps the flow of `enqueue` and `dequeue` operations in a **linear queue**, including the boundary checks that the C program performs.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    startOp([User Selects Operation]) --> checkOp{Operation Type?}
    checkOp -- Enqueue --> chkFullL{rear == MAX - 1?}
    chkFullL -- Yes --> ovfL[/Print Queue Overflow/]
    ovfL --> endOp([Return to Menu])
    chkFullL -- No --> incRearL[rear = rear + 1]
    incRearL --> insL[queue rear = item]
    insL --> endOp
    checkOp -- Dequeue --> chkEmptyL{front == -1 OR front > rear?}
    chkEmptyL -- Yes --> unfL[/Print Queue Underflow/]
    unfL --> endOp
    chkEmptyL -- No --> retL[item = queue front]
    retL --> incFrontL[front = front + 1]
    incFrontL --> resetL{front > rear?}
    resetL -- Yes --> resetBothL[front = rear = -1]
    resetBothL --> endOp
    resetL -- No --> endOp
    checkOp -- Display --> dispL[Loop from front to rear, print queue i]
    dispL --> endOp
```

## 4.2 Circular Queue — Block-Level Functional Architecture

The following diagram illustrates the **circular queue's** operation flow, emphasizing the **modulo arithmetic** and the **single-slot-sacrificed** overflow detection.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    startOpC([User Selects Operation]) --> checkOpC{Operation Type?}
    checkOpC -- Enqueue --> chkFullC{rear + 1 mod MAX equals front?}
    chkFullC -- Yes --> ovfC[/Print Queue Overflow/]
    ovfC --> endOpC([Return to Menu])
    chkFullC -- No --> chkFirst{front == -1?}
    chkFirst -- Yes --> setFrontC[front = 0]
    setFrontC --> incRearC[rear = rear + 1 mod MAX]
    chkFirst -- No --> incRearC
    incRearC --> insC[queue rear = item]
    insC --> endOpC
    checkOpC -- Dequeue --> chkEmptyC{front == -1?}
    chkEmptyC -- Yes --> unfC[/Print Queue Underflow/]
    unfC --> endOpC
    chkEmptyC -- No --> retC[item = queue front]
    retC --> chkLast{front == rear?}
    chkLast -- Yes --> resetBothC[front = rear = -1]
    resetBothC --> endOpC
    chkLast -- No --> incFrontC[front = front + 1 mod MAX]
    incFrontC --> endOpC
    checkOpC -- Display --> cntC[count = MAX - front + rear + 1 mod MAX]
    cntC --> loopC[i = 0 to count - 1]
    loopC --> idxC[index = front + i mod MAX]
    idxC --> printC[Print queue index]
    printC --> endOpC
```

## 4.3 Circular Queue — Visual Ring Representation

The following diagram is a **logical ring view** of the same circular queue state obtained at the end of Section 3.3 (after Operation 7).

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    slot0["Index 0 : 60"] --> slot1["Index 1 : 20"]
    slot1 --> slot2["Index 2 : 30"]
    slot2 --> slot3["Index 3 : 40"]
    slot3 --> slot4["Index 4 : 50"]
    slot4 -.wrap.-> slot0
    noteR["REAR points here"] -.-> slot0
    noteF["FRONT points here"] -.-> slot1
```

> [!NOTE]
> **How to read this diagram**: The arrows show the logical "next" direction in the circular array. The dashed wrap-around arrow from `Index 4` back to `Index 0` represents the modulo connection. `REAR` is at slot `0` (the most recently inserted element `60`) and `FRONT` is at slot `1` (the next element to be dequeued, `20`). The slot at `0` is the one that would be overwritten by the **next** enqueue (which would then overflow, as we verified in Operation 8).

## 4.4 Reference C Program — Implementation of Queue Using Array

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 5

int queue[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;

void enqueue() {
    int item;
    if (rear == MAX - 1) {
        printf("\nQueue Overflow! Cannot insert.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("Enter element to insert: ");
    scanf("%d", &item);
    if (front == -1) front = 0;
    rear = rear + 1;
    queue[rear] = item;
    printf("%d inserted.\n", item);
}

void dequeue() {
    int item;
    if (front == -1 || front > rear) {
        printf("\nQueue Underflow! Cannot delete.\n");
        return;
    }
    item = queue[front];
    printf("%d deleted.\n", item);
    front = front + 1;
    if (front > rear) front = rear = -1;
}

void display() {
    int i;
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("\nQueue is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("\nQueue elements are:\n");
    for (i = front; i <= rear; i++)
        printf("%d\t", queue[i]);
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    int choice;
    while (1) {
        printf("\n--- LINEAR QUEUE MENU ---\n");
        printf("1. Enqueue\n2. Dequeue\n3. Display\n4. Exit\n");
        printf("Enter choice: ");
        scanf("%d", &choice);
        switch (choice) {
            case 1: enqueue(); break;
            case 2: dequeue(); break;
            case 3: display(); break;
            case 4: return 0;
            default: printf("Invalid choice.\n");
        }
    }
}
```

## 4.5 Reference C Program — Implementation of Circular Queue Using Array

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 5

int cqueue[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;

void cenqueue() {
    int item;
    if ((rear + 1) % MAX == front) {
        printf("\nCircular Queue Overflow!\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("Enter element to insert: ");
    scanf("%d", &item);
    if (front == -1) front = 0;
    rear = (rear + 1) % MAX;
    cqueue[rear] = item;
    printf("%d inserted.\n", item);
}

void cdequeue() {
    int item;
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("\nCircular Queue Underflow!\n");
        return;
    }
    item = cqueue[front];
    printf("%d deleted.\n", item);
    if (front == rear)
        front = rear = -1;
    else
        front = (front + 1) % MAX;
}

void cdisplay() {
    int i, count;
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("\nCircular Queue is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("\nCircular Queue elements:\n");
    count = (MAX - front + rear) % MAX;
    for (i = 1; i <= count; i++) {
        printf("%d\t", cqueue[(front + i - 1) % MAX]);
    }
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    int choice;
    while (1) {
        printf("\n--- CIRCULAR QUEUE MENU ---\n");
        printf("1. Enqueue\n2. Dequeue\n3. Display\n4. Exit\n");
        printf("Enter choice: ");
        scanf("%d", &choice);
        switch (choice) {
            case 1: cenqueue(); break;
            case 2: cdequeue(); break;
            case 3: cdisplay(); break;
            case 4: return 0;
            default: printf("Invalid choice.\n");
        }
    }
}
```

