# Section 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`
**Define a queue data structure. Mention any two real-world applications where queues are used.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

> A queue is a linear data structure that follows the **FIFO (First-In, First-Out)** principle. Insertion occurs at the **rear** end and deletion occurs at the **front** end.
>
> **Real-world applications:**
> 1. **CPU Scheduling** in operating systems (e.g., Round Robin scheduling uses a circular queue of ready processes).
> 2. **Disk Scheduling** — request queue management.
> 3. **Printer Spooling** — print jobs are processed in arrival order.
> 4. **Call Center Systems** — calls are handled in the order they were received.

*(Award 1 mark for definition, 1 mark each for any two applications — max 3 marks.)*

---

### Question 2 `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`
**Differentiate between a linear queue and a circular queue. State one limitation of a linear queue.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Parameter | Linear Queue | Circular Queue |
|---|---|---|
| Index behavior | `rear` increases linearly until `MAX - 1` | `rear` wraps around using modulo |
| Memory reuse | Cannot reuse freed front slots | Reuses freed slots via `(rear + 1) % MAX` |
| Overflow type | False overflow possible | Only true overflow |
| Implementation | Simpler | Slightly more complex |

**Limitation of linear queue**: It suffers from **false overflow** — once `rear` reaches `MAX - 1`, no more insertions are allowed even if `front` has moved forward and slots are free.

*(Award 2 marks for the comparison, 1 mark for stating the limitation.)*

---

## 5.2 Part B — Essay Questions (14 Marks Each, Module Internal Choice)

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Common Pitfalls**
> 1. **Forgetting the `front == -1` first-element check** in `enqueue` — examiners deduct **1 full mark** for this in both linear and circular variants.
> 2. **Using the wrong overflow condition** in circular queue (`rear == MAX - 1` instead of `(rear + 1) % MAX == front`) is the most common mistake — leads to **2 marks deduction**.
> 3. **Not resetting `front` and `rear` to `-1`** after the queue becomes empty post-deletion — results in **incorrect `isEmpty` checks later**, costing 1 mark.
> 4. **Confusing `display` traversal** — students print all `MAX` slots instead of only the valid elements between `front` and `rear`. Deduct **1 mark**.
> 5. **Tracing errors in modular arithmetic** — `(rear + 1) % MAX` is often written as `(rear++) % MAX`, which is **logically incorrect** in C because `rear` is updated before the modulo is applied to the *old* value.

---

### Question A (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023, Modified]`

**(a)** Write the algorithm for **enqueue** and **dequeue** operations on a **circular queue** implemented using an array of size `MAX = 6`. Clearly state the **overflow** and **underflow** conditions. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Trace the execution of the following operations on an initially empty circular queue of size `MAX = 6` and show the state of `front`, `rear`, and the array after each operation:  
**Enqueue 5, Enqueue 10, Enqueue 15, Dequeue, Enqueue 20, Enqueue 25, Enqueue 30, Enqueue 35, Enqueue 40, Dequeue.** **(7 marks)**

---

### Model Solution — Question A

#### Part (a) — Algorithm (7 marks)

**Data Members:**

```
int cqueue[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;
```

**Overflow Condition:**

$$(\text{rear} + 1) \bmod \text{MAX} == \text{front}$$

**Underflow Condition:**

$$\text{front} == -1$$

**Algorithm — `cenqueue(item)`:**

```
Step 1: IF ((rear + 1) MOD MAX) == front
            PRINT "Circular Queue Overflow"
            RETURN
        END IF
Step 2: IF front == -1
            SET front = 0
        END IF
Step 3: SET rear = (rear + 1) MOD MAX
Step 4: SET cqueue[rear] = item
Step 5: PRINT "Inserted", item
Step 6: RETURN
```

**Algorithm — `cdequeue()`:**

```
Step 1: IF front == -1
            PRINT "Circular Queue Underflow"
            RETURN
        END IF
Step 2: SET item = cqueue[front]
Step 3: PRINT "Deleted", item
Step 4: IF front == rear
            SET front = rear = -1
        ELSE
            SET front = (front + 1) MOD MAX
        END IF
Step 5: RETURN
```

*(Award 1 mark for data members, 1 mark for conditions, 3 marks for enqueue algorithm, 2 marks for dequeue algorithm.)*

---

#### Part (b) — Trace Table (7 marks)

| Step | Operation | front | rear | Array (Index 0..5) | Remarks |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 0 | Init | -1 | -1 | `[_, _, _, _, _, _]` | Empty queue |
| 1 | Enq 5 | 0 | 0 | `[5, _, _, _, _, _]` | First element triggers `front = 0` |
| 2 | Enq 10 | 0 | 1 | `[5, 10, _, _, _, _]` | Normal increment |
| 3 | Enq 15 | 0 | 2 | `[5, 10, 15, _, _, _]` | Normal increment |
| 4 | Deq | 1 | 2 | `[_, 10, 15, _, _, _]` | Returns 5; `front` becomes 1 |
| 5 | Enq 20 | 1 | 3 | `[_, 10, 15, 20, _, _]` | Normal increment |
| 6 | Enq 25 | 1 | 4 | `[_, 10, 15, 20, 25, _]` | Normal increment |
| 7 | Enq 30 | 1 | 5 | `[_, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30]` | Reaches boundary |
| 8 | Enq 35 | 1 | 0 | `[35, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30]` | **WRAP!** $(5+1)\%6 = 0$ |
| 9 | Enq 40 | 1 | 1 | `[35, 40, 15, 20, 25, 30]` | rear now equals front... wait, check overflow first |
| 9' | Overflow Check | — | — | — | $(1+1)\%6 = 2 \neq 1$ → NOT full. Insert OK. rear=2. `[35, 40, 15, 20, 25, 30]` with front=1, rear=2 |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Correction Note for Step 9**: After Step 8, `front = 1, rear = 0`. Now `(rear + 1) % 6 = (0+1) % 6 = 1`. Since `1 == front`, this means **OVERFLOW!** The queue is full with 5 elements (slots 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 occupied, slot 0 is the sacrificed empty slot). So Step 9 reports **overflow** — element 40 is **not inserted**.

| Step | Operation | front | rear | Array (Index 0..5) | Remarks |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 9 | Enq 40 | 1 | 0 | `[35, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30]` | **OVERFLOW** — slot `0` is sacrificed |
| 10 | Deq | 2 | 0 | `[35, _, 15, 20, 25, 30]` | Returns 10; `front` becomes 2 |

*(Award 1 mark for each correct row, 7 rows × 1 mark = 7 marks.)*

