### Model Solution — Question B

#### Part (a) — False Overflow Explanation (7 marks)

**False Overflow** is a phenomenon in which a linear queue reports the **overflow** condition even though there are **vacant slots** at the front of the array that are not being used.

**Illustration:**

Suppose `MAX = 5` and the queue has undergone the following operations:

1. Enqueue 10, 20, 30, 40, 50 → `rear = 4, front = 0`, **full**.
2. Dequeue (twice) → removes 10 and 20. Now `front = 2, rear = 4`. Slots `0` and `1` are free.

**Diagram of the queue state:**

```
Index:    0     1     2     3     4
       +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+
Value: |     |     | 30  | 40  | 50  |
       +-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+
            ^                 ^
         (FREE)             rear = 4
                           front = 2
```

If we now attempt **Enqueue 60**, the linear queue will report **OVERFLOW** because `rear == MAX - 1 = 4`, even though slots `0` and `1` are completely free.

**How circular queue overcomes this**: The circular queue uses **modulo arithmetic** to wrap `rear` back to `0` after it reaches `MAX - 1`. Hence, after dequeue, the free slots at the front can be reused for future insertions.

**Overflow condition for circular queue:**

$$(\text{rear} + 1) \bmod \text{MAX} == \text{front}$$

*(Award 2 marks for explanation, 2 marks for diagram, 2 marks for circular queue solution, 1 mark for the overflow formula.)*

---

#### Part (b) — Complete C Program (7 marks)

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 10

int queue[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;

void enqueue() {
    int item;
    if (rear == MAX - 1) {
        printf("\nQueue Overflow!\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("Enter element: ");
    scanf("%d", &item);
    if (front == -1) front = 0;
    rear++;
    queue[rear] = item;
    printf("%d inserted.\n", item);
}

void dequeue() {
    if (front == -1 || front > rear) {
        printf("\nQueue Underflow!\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("%d deleted.\n", queue[front]);
    front++;
    if (front > rear) front = rear = -1;
}

void peek() {
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("\nQueue is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("Front element: %d\n", queue[front]);
}

void display() {
    int i;
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("\nQueue is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("Queue: ");
    for (i = front; i <= rear; i++)
        printf("%d ", queue[i]);
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    int ch;
    while (1) {
        printf("\n1.Enqueue 2.Dequeue 3.Peek 4.Display 5.Exit\n");
        printf("Enter choice: ");
        scanf("%d", &ch);
        switch (ch) {
            case 1: enqueue(); break;
            case 2: dequeue(); break;
            case 3: peek(); break;
            case 4: display(); break;
            case 5: return 0;
            default: printf("Invalid!\n");
        }
    }
}
```

