# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Sorting** is the fundamental algorithmic operation of rearranging the elements of a finite sequence $(a_1, a_2, a_3, \dots, a_n)$ into a monotonic order — either **non-decreasing** (ascending: $a_1 \le a_2 \le a_3 \le \dots \le a_n$) or **non-increasing** (descending: $a_1 \ge a_2 \ge \dots \ge a_n$) — typically based on a chosen **key value** within each data record.

A **comparison-based sorting algorithm** is one whose decision at every step is governed entirely by pairwise comparator operations of the form $\text{cmp}(a_i, a_j) \in \{-1, 0, +1\}$. All five algorithms studied in this experiment — Bubble, Insertion, Selection, Quick, and Merge Sort — belong to this class. They differ in their **worst-case time complexity**, **auxiliary space usage**, **in-place property**, and **stability**.

> [!NOTE]
> **Stability** means that two records with equal keys retain their original relative order after sorting. This is critical in real-world databases where secondary keys matter.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy (Plain-English Intuition)

Imagine you are a **school teacher** with a stack of answer sheets. You want to arrange them roll-number-wise.

- **Bubble Sort** = You walk through the pile repeatedly. Every time you find two adjacent sheets out of order, you swap them. The "biggest" sheet keeps bubbling up to the end, just like a heavy bubble rising to the surface of water.
- **Insertion Sort** = You take sheets **one by one** and slide each new sheet into its correct slot among the already-sorted cards in your hand — exactly like arranging playing cards.
- **Selection Sort** = You scan the entire pile, **find the smallest sheet**, and place it at position 1. Then find the next smallest, place at position 2, and so on.
- **Quick Sort** = You pick one sheet as a **pivot**, put all sheets smaller than it on the left and all larger on the right (this is one round of *partition*). Then you recursively repeat this on the left and right sub-piles.
- **Merge Sort** = You split the pile into single sheets (**divide**), then repeatedly merge pairs of sorted piles back into bigger sorted piles (**conquer**). It is the classic *divide-and-conquer* strategy.

## 1.3 Core Vocabulary Anchored to the Syllabus

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **In-place** | Uses only $O(1)$ extra memory beyond the input array |
| **Stable** | Preserves relative order of equal-keyed elements |
| **Comparison Sort** | Determines order using only element comparisons |
| **Adaptive** | Performs fewer operations on partially-sorted input |
| **Divide and Conquer** | Recursively splits problem into sub-problems, then combines results |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Standard metrics used in KTU 2024 lab evaluations: **Time Complexity** $T(n)$, **Space Complexity** $S(n)$, **Number of Comparisons** $C(n)$, and **Number of Swaps / Moves** $M(n)$.
