# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Algorithm-by-Algorithm Operational Breakdown

### 2.1.1 Bubble Sort
Repeatedly traverses the array, comparing adjacent pairs. After pass $i$ (0-indexed), the element at index $n-1-i$ is guaranteed to be in its final sorted position (the "bubbled up" maximum).

**Logic Steps:**
1. Outer loop runs $n-1$ passes.
2. Inner loop compares $a[j]$ with $a[j+1]$ for $j = 0 \dots n-2-i$.
3. If $a[j] > a[j+1]$, perform an **adjacent swap** (in-place).
4. Optional early-exit flag `swapped` — if a pass makes no swaps, the array is sorted.

### 2.1.2 Insertion Sort
Maintains a sorted prefix $[0 \dots i-1]$ and inserts element $a[i]$ into its correct position within that prefix by shifting larger elements rightward.

**Logic Steps:**
1. Start with $i = 1$ (single element is trivially sorted).
2. Store `key = a[i]`.
3. Shift all elements $> \text{key}$ in $a[0 \dots i-1]$ one position to the right.
4. Place `key` in the vacated slot.

### 2.1.3 Selection Sort
Finds the minimum element in $a[i \dots n-1]$ and swaps it with $a[i]$. Increases the sorted suffix by one element per pass.

**Logic Steps:**
1. For each $i = 0 \dots n-2$, scan $j = i+1 \dots n-1$ tracking the index `min_idx` of the smallest element.
2. Swap $a[i]$ and $a[\text{min\_idx}]$.

### 2.1.4 Quick Sort (Divide and Conquer — Partition based)
Selects a **pivot** and partitions the array such that elements $\le$ pivot lie to its left and elements $>$ pivot lie to its right. Recursively sorts the two partitions.

**Logic Steps (Lomuto Partition):**
1. Choose pivot (commonly the last element, $a[\text{high}]$).
2. Maintain `i = low - 1`. For $j = \text{low} \dots \text{high}-1$, if $a[j] \le \text{pivot}$, increment `i` and swap $a[i]$ with $a[j]$.
3. Finally swap $a[i+1]$ with $a[\text{high}]$. Return $i+1$ as partition index.
4. Recurse on $[\text{low} \dots p-1]$ and $[p+1 \dots \text{high}]$.

### 2.1.5 Merge Sort (Divide and Conquer — Merging based)
Recursively splits the array into halves until single elements remain, then **merges** them in sorted order using an auxiliary buffer.

**Logic Steps:**
1. If $\text{low} < \text{high}$, set $\text{mid} = \lfloor(\text{low}+\text{high})/2\rfloor$.
2. Recursively sort the left half $a[\text{low} \dots \text{mid}]$.
3. Recursively sort the right half $a[\text{mid}+1 \dots \text{high}]$.
4. **Merge** the two sorted halves using a temporary array.

## 2.2 KTU High-Yield Formula / Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> The following table is the **#1 revision artifact** for any KTU Data Structures exam question on sorting. Memorize the recurrences and stability flags.

| Algorithm | Best Case $T(n)$ | Average Case $T(n)$ | Worst Case $T(n)$ | Recurrence $T(n)$ | Space $S(n)$ | Stable? | In-place? |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Bubble Sort | $\Omega(n)$ | $\Theta(n^{2})$ | $O(n^{2})$ | $T(n) = T(n-1) + n - 1$ | $O(1)$ | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Insertion Sort | $\Omega(n)$ | $\Theta(n^{2})$ | $O(n^{2})$ | $T(n) = T(n-1) + n - 1$ | $O(1)$ | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Selection Sort | $\Theta(n^{2})$ | $\Theta(n^{2})$ | $\Theta(n^{2})$ | $T(n) = T(n-1) + n - 1$ | $O(1)$ | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Quick Sort | $\Omega(n \log n)$ | $\Theta(n \log n)$ | $O(n^{2})$ | $T(n) = T(k) + T(n-1-k) + n$ | $O(\log n)$ stack | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Merge Sort | $\Omega(n \log n)$ | $\Theta(n \log n)$ | $\Theta(n \log n)$ | $T(n) = 2T(n/2) + n$ | $O(n)$ | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Quick Sort worst case** $O(n^{2})$ occurs when the pivot is always the smallest or largest element (e.g., already-sorted input with last-element pivot). **Merge Sort** is the only algorithm of these five with guaranteed $O(n \log n)$ worst-case time.

## 2.3 Comparison / Swap Counts (Auxiliary Metric)

| Algorithm | Comparisons $C(n)$ Worst | Swaps/Moves $M(n)$ Worst |
|---|---|---|
| Bubble Sort | $\frac{n(n-1)}{2}$ | $\frac{n(n-1)}{2}$ |
| Insertion Sort | $\frac{n(n-1)}{2}$ | $\frac{n(n-1)}{2}$ |
| Selection Sort | $\frac{n(n-1)}{2}$ | $n-1$ |
| Quick Sort | $\frac{n(n-1)}{2}$ | $\frac{n(n-1)}{2}$ |
| Merge Sort | $n \log_2 n - n + 1$ | $2n \log_2 n$ |

## 2.4 Engineering Utility

- **Bubble Sort** is almost never used in production; it is taught for its didactic value (introducing swap-based sorting).
- **Insertion Sort** is the fastest algorithm for **very small arrays** ($n \le 15$) and is therefore the **base case** of optimized Quick Sort and TimSort (used in Python and Java's `Arrays.sort`).
- **Selection Sort** minimizes the number of writes — useful when writes to memory (e.g., EEPROM/flash) are expensive.
- **Quick Sort** is the **default** in most standard C/C++ `qsort` implementations and Java's primitive-type `Dual-Pivot Quick Sort`.
- **Merge Sort** is the standard choice for **external sorting** (sorting files larger than RAM) and for **linked-list sorting**, because it has predictable $O(n \log n)$ time and works seamlessly with sequential access.
