# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Derivation of Quick Sort Worst-Case Recurrence

The Quick Sort recurrence depends on the partition sizes produced by the pivot.

**General Recurrence:**
$$
T(n) = T(k) + T(n - 1 - k) + \Theta(n)
$$

where $k$ is the number of elements on the left of the pivot and $\Theta(n)$ is the cost of the partition scan.

**Case 1 — Worst case (perfectly unbalanced partition, $k = 0$ or $k = n-1$):**
$$
\begin{aligned}
T(n) &= T(0) + T(n - 1) + cn \\
     &= T(n - 1) + cn \\
     &= T(n - 2) + c(n - 1) + cn \\
     &= \dots \\
     &= T(1) + c \sum_{i=2}^{n} i \\
     &= c \cdot \frac{n(n+1)}{2} - O(n) \\
     &= \Theta(n^{2})
\end{aligned}
$$

The substitution unfolds because each recursive call peels off exactly **one** element, producing $n$ stack frames each costing $O(n)$ for partitioning.

**Case 2 — Best case (perfectly balanced partition, $k = \lfloor n/2 \rfloor$):**
$$
T(n) = 2\,T(n/2) + cn
$$

By the **Master Theorem** (Case 2 with $a = 2$, $b = 2$, $f(n) = n$, so $n^{\log_b a} = n^{1}$ and $f(n) = \Theta(n^{\log_b a})$):
$$
T(n) = \Theta(n \log_2 n)
$$

> [!NOTE]
> KTU examiners frequently expect you to derive the recurrence first and **then apply the Master Theorem** — not jump straight to the answer.

## 3.2 Derivation of Merge Sort Recurrence via Master Theorem

Merge Sort splits the array into two equal halves, sorts each, then performs an $O(n)$ merge.

**Recurrence:**
$$
T(n) = 2\,T\!\left(\tfrac{n}{2}\right) + \Theta(n)
$$

Here $a = 2$, $b = 2$, $f(n) = n$, so $n^{\log_b a} = n^{1}$. Since $f(n) = \Theta(n^{\log_b a})$, this falls under **Master Theorem Case 2**:
$$
T(n) = \Theta\!\left(n^{\log_b a} \log n\right) = \Theta(n \log_2 n)
$$

**Detailed unfolding proof:**
$$
\begin{aligned}
T(n) &= 2T(n/2) + cn \\
     &= 2\left[2T(n/4) + c(n/2)\right] + cn = 4T(n/4) + 2cn \\
     &= 4\left[2T(n/8) + c(n/4)\right] + 2cn = 8T(n/8) + 3cn \\
     &\;\;\vdots \\
     &= 2^{k} T(n/2^{k}) + kcn
\end{aligned}
$$

The recursion bottoms out when $n/2^{k} = 1$, i.e. when $k = \log_2 n$. Substituting:
$$
T(n) = 2^{\log_2 n} \cdot T(1) + cn \log_2 n = n \cdot T(1) + cn \log_2 n = \Theta(n \log n)
$$

## 3.3 Bubble Sort Pass-by-Pass Trace (Worked Example)

Sort the array $A = [5, 1, 4, 2, 8]$ using Bubble Sort. Here $n = 5$, so we run **4 passes**.

| Pass $i$ | Array State (after each swap) | Comments |
|---|---|---|
| Start | `[5, 1, 4, 2, 8]` | Unsorted |
| Pass 1 | `[1, 5, 4, 2, 8]` → `[1, 4, 5, 2, 8]` → `[1, 4, 2, 5, 8]` → `[1, 4, 2, 5, 8]` | Largest element `8` has bubbled to the end |
| Pass 2 | `[1, 4, 2, 5, 8]` → `[1, 2, 4, 5, 8]` → `[1, 2, 4, 5, 8]` | `5` is now at index 3 (its final place) |
| Pass 3 | `[1, 2, 4, 5, 8]` → `[1, 2, 4, 5, 8]` | Already sorted — pass with no swaps detected |
| Pass 4 | (skipped if `swapped` flag is used) | Early termination |

**Total comparisons:** $\frac{5(5-1)}{2} = 10$ in the worst case; here we used fewer due to early termination.

## 3.4 Analytical Comparison Matrix (Decision-Making Aid)

| Use this algorithm when… | Avoid this algorithm when… |
|---|---|
| Array is small ($n \le 15$) → Insertion Sort | Data is huge and already nearly random → Insertion Sort |
| Worst-case guarantee is critical → Merge Sort | Memory is severely constrained → Merge Sort |
| Average-case speed matters more than worst case → Quick Sort | Stability is required + recursion depth must be bounded → Quick Sort |
| Writes are expensive (e.g., flash memory) → Selection Sort | Code clarity is the priority → Quick Sort (use Insertion Sort) |
| Teaching swaps and passes → Bubble Sort | Real production systems → Bubble Sort |

## 3.5 Reference C Implementations (KTU Lab Standard)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> KTU lab evaluations expect ANSI-C programs with proper indentation, comments, modular functions, and a `main()` that reads input and prints the sorted array. The following are **complete, compilable reference programs** for each algorithm.

### 3.5.1 Bubble Sort in C
```c
#include <stdio.h>

void bubbleSort(int a[], int n) {
    int i, j, temp, swapped;
    for (i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        swapped = 0;
        for (j = 0; j < n - 1 - i; j++) {
            if (a[j] > a[j + 1]) {
                temp = a[j];
                a[j] = a[j + 1];
                a[j + 1] = temp;
                swapped = 1;
            }
        }
        if (swapped == 0) break;   // already sorted
    }
}

int main(void) {
    int a[] = {5, 1, 4, 2, 8};
    int n = sizeof(a) / sizeof(a[0]);
    bubbleSort(a, n);
    printf("Sorted array: ");
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) printf("%d ", a[i]);
    printf("\n");
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.5.2 Insertion Sort in C
```c
#include <stdio.h>

void insertionSort(int a[], int n) {
    int i, j, key;
    for (i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        key = a[i];
        j = i - 1;
        while (j >= 0 && a[j] > key) {
            a[j + 1] = a[j];
            j--;
        }
        a[j + 1] = key;
    }
}

int main(void) {
    int a[] = {12, 11, 13, 5, 6};
    int n = 5;
    insertionSort(a, n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) printf("%d ", a[i]);
    printf("\n");
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.5.3 Selection Sort in C
```c
#include <stdio.h>

void selectionSort(int a[], int n) {
    int i, j, minIdx, temp;
    for (i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        minIdx = i;
        for (j = i + 1; j < n; j++)
            if (a[j] < a[minIdx]) minIdx = j;
        if (minIdx != i) {
            temp = a[i]; a[i] = a[minIdx]; a[minIdx] = temp;
        }
    }
}

int main(void) {
    int a[] = {64, 25, 12, 22, 11};
    int n = 5;
    selectionSort(a, n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) printf("%d ", a[i]);
    printf("\n");
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.5.4 Quick Sort in C (Lomuto Partition)
```c
#include <stdio.h>

int partition(int a[], int low, int high) {
    int pivot = a[high];     // choose last element as pivot
    int i = low - 1, j, temp;
    for (j = low; j < high; j++) {
        if (a[j] <= pivot) {
            i++;
            temp = a[i]; a[i] = a[j]; a[j] = temp;
        }
    }
    temp = a[i + 1]; a[i + 1] = a[high]; a[high] = temp;
    return i + 1;
}

void quickSort(int a[], int low, int high) {
    if (low < high) {
        int pi = partition(a, low, high);
        quickSort(a, low, pi - 1);
        quickSort(a, pi + 1, high);
    }
}

int main(void) {
    int a[] = {10, 7, 8, 9, 1, 5};
    int n = 6;
    quickSort(a, 0, n - 1);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) printf("%d ", a[i]);
    printf("\n");
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.5.5 Merge Sort in C
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

void merge(int a[], int l, int m, int r) {
    int i, j, k;
    int n1 = m - l + 1, n2 = r - m;
    int *L = (int *)malloc(n1 * sizeof(int));
    int *R = (int *)malloc(n2 * sizeof(int));
    for (i = 0; i < n1; i++) L[i] = a[l + i];
    for (j = 0; j < n2; j++) R[j] = a[m + 1 + j];
    i = j = 0; k = l;
    while (i < n1 && j < n2) a[k++] = (L[i] <= R[j]) ? L[i++] : R[j++];
    while (i < n1) a[k++] = L[i++];
    while (j < n2) a[k++] = R[j++];
    free(L); free(R);
}

void mergeSort(int a[], int l, int r) {
    if (l < r) {
        int m = l + (r - l) / 2;
        mergeSort(a, l, m);
        mergeSort(a, m + 1, r);
        merge(a, l, m, r);
    }
}

int main(void) {
    int a[] = {38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10};
    int n = 7;
    mergeSort(a, 0, n - 1);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) printf("%d ", a[i]);
    printf("\n");
    return 0;
}
```

