### ❓ Question B — 14 Marks (Alternative Choice)

> **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2024]**

**(a)** Write the algorithm/pseudocode for **Merge Sort**. Demonstrate its working on the array $A = \{38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10\}$ by drawing the recursive call tree and showing the state after each merge operation. (7 marks)

**(b)** Discuss the **time complexity** of Merge Sort in best, average, and worst cases, and state the recurrence relation. Why is Merge Sort preferred for sorting **linked lists** and for **external sorting**? (7 marks)

---

#### Model Solution — Q B(a)

**Algorithm:**
```
MERGESORT(A, low, high):
    if low < high:
        mid = (low + high) / 2
        MERGESORT(A, low, mid)
        MERGESORT(A, mid + 1, high)
        MERGE(A, low, mid, high)

MERGE(A, low, mid, high):
    n1 = mid - low + 1;  n2 = high - mid
    create L[0..n1-1], R[0..n2-1]
    copy A[low..mid] into L; copy A[mid+1..high] into R
    i = j = 0; k = low
    while i < n1 and j < n2:
        if L[i] <= R[j]: A[k++] = L[i++]
        else: A[k++] = R[j++]
    copy remaining L and R into A
```

**Recursive Call Tree & Merge Stages for $A = \{38, 27, 43, 3, 9, 82, 10\}$:**

| Stage | Sub-array | Action | Result |
|---|---|---|---|
| Divide Level 3 | $\{38\}, \{27\}, \{43\}, \{3\}, \{9\}, \{82\}, \{10\}$ | Trivially sorted | Same |
| Merge Level 2 | $\{38, 27\} \to \{27, 38\}$ | Merge | $\{27, 38\}$ |
| Merge Level 2 | $\{43, 3\} \to \{3, 43\}$ | Merge | $\{3, 43\}$ |
| Merge Level 2 | $\{9, 82\} \to \{9, 82\}$ | Merge | $\{9, 82\}$ |
| Merge Level 2 | $\{10\}$ | Single | $\{10\}$ |
| Merge Level 1 | $\{27, 38, 3, 43\}$ | Merge | $\{3, 27, 38, 43\}$ |
| Merge Level 1 | $\{9, 82, 10\}$ | Merge | $\{9, 10, 82\}$ |
| Merge Level 0 | $\{3, 27, 38, 43, 9, 10, 82\}$ | Final Merge | $\{3, 9, 10, 27, 38, 43, 82\}$ |

**Marking scheme (7 marks):**
- Pseudocode (correct recursion + correct merge): **3 marks**.
- Recursion tree / divide phase: **2 marks**.
- Merge phase table or final result: **2 marks**.

---

#### Model Solution — Q B(b)

**Recurrence Relation:**
$$
T(n) = 2\,T\!\left(\tfrac{n}{2}\right) + \Theta(n)
$$

The $\Theta(n)$ term represents the cost of merging two sorted halves of total size $n$.

**Solving via Master Theorem:** $a = 2$, $b = 2$, $f(n) = n$, so $n^{\log_b a} = n^{1}$. Since $f(n) = \Theta(n^{\log_b a})$, by Case 2:
$$
T(n) = \Theta(n \log_2 n) \quad \text{for all cases (best, average, worst)}
$$

Merge Sort exhibits the **same time complexity in all three cases**, which is its most prized property.

**Why Merge Sort for Linked Lists?**
1. Linked lists do not support random access in $O(1)$, which cripples Quick Sort's pivot-based partitioning.
2. Merge Sort's merge step only requires **sequential traversal** — perfect for pointer-based data.
3. The merging of two sorted linked lists can be done **in-place** by re-linking nodes (no extra $O(n)$ buffer needed).

**Why Merge Sort for External Sorting?**
1. External data (e.g., a 100 GB log file) cannot fit into RAM.
2. Merge Sort naturally splits the file into **runs** small enough to fit in memory, sorts each run, then performs a **multi-way merge** using disk streams.
3. Sequential reads/writes minimize expensive **disk seek operations**.

**Marking scheme (7 marks):**
- Correct recurrence: **2 marks**.
- Master Theorem application + conclusion: **2 marks**.
- Linked-list argument: **1.5 marks**.
- External-sorting argument: **1.5 marks**.

