## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mark-Deduction Pitfalls — Read Carefully!**
>
> 1. **Forgetting base cases** in Quick Sort recursion: writing `quickSort(a, 0, n)` instead of `quickSort(a, 0, n-1)` triggers an out-of-bounds access and **2-mark deduction**.
> 2. **Off-by-one in Merge Sort midpoint**: using `mid = (low + high) / 2` is correct, but **calling** `mergeSort(a, mid, high)` instead of `mergeSort(a, mid+1, high)` causes infinite recursion on the right half — **2-mark deduction**.
> 3. **Confusing stability**: Several students claim Quick Sort is stable because it uses `<=` in the comparator. The Lomuto scheme **does** swap equal-keyed elements across the pivot, breaking stability — **1-mark deduction** per wrong claim.
> 4. **Stating Merge Sort is in-place**: Merge Sort allocates an auxiliary $O(n)$ array; it is **not in-place** — **1-mark deduction**.
> 5. **Wrong time complexity for Bubble Sort best case**: writing $O(n^{2})$ instead of $\Omega(n)$. Examiners distinguish upper bound ($O$) from lower bound ($\Omega$) — **1-mark deduction**.
> 6. **Skipping trace tables**: A correct algorithm without the requested trace gets at most **3 of 7 marks** for that sub-part. Always draw the table.

