## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!NOTE]
> **Doubly Linked List (DLL):** A linear, dynamic data structure consisting of a sequence of **nodes**, where each node contains three fields: a **data** field, a pointer to the **previous** node (`prev`), and a pointer to the **next** node (`next`). Unlike a singly linked list, a DLL allows traversal in **both forward and backward** directions with a time complexity of **O(1)** for node access from either end.

The structural definition of a node in a Doubly Linked List, as per the KTU 2024 syllabus (aligned with *Fundamentals of Data Structures in C* by Horowitz & Sahni, and *Data Structures* by Tenenbaum), is given as:

$$
\text{Node} = \{ \text{data}, \ \text{prev pointer}, \ \text{next pointer} \}
$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight (PCITL308 - Module 2):** Students must be able to *implement, trace, and analyze* the four core DLL operations — **Traversing**, **Searching**, **Insertion** (at beginning, end, given position), and **Deletion** (from beginning, end, given position). Viva questions typically focus on **pointer manipulation** and **boundary conditions** (empty list, single node, head/tail pointers).

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuitive Overview

Imagine a **train with a coupling link on BOTH ends of every coach**:

- Each **coach** is a **node** containing passengers (**data**).
- The **front coupling** of a coach points to the coach ahead of it (`next` pointer).
- The **rear coupling** of a coach points to the coach behind it (`prev` pointer).
- The **engine** at the front is the **HEAD** pointer (start of the list).
- The **last coach's front coupling** points to `NULL` (no coach ahead).

> [!TIP]
> **Why "Doubly"?** Because just as you can walk **forward** through the train from engine to last coach, you can also walk **backward** from the last coach back to the engine — both directions are accessible. This is the key advantage over a singly linked list (SLL), which is like a one-way escalator — you can only go forward (or restart from head to go back).

**Key Standard Metrics:**

- **Node Size:** 1 (data) + 1 (next pointer) + 1 (prev pointer) = **3 memory units** per node
- **Pointer Overhead:** **2 pointers per node** (vs. 1 in SLL)
- **Time per Node Access:** **O(1)** (constant time pointer dereference)
- **Traversal Time (n nodes):** **O(n)** linear time

### 1.3 Comparison Table — DLL vs SLL

| Property | Singly Linked List | Doubly Linked List |
|---|---|---|
| Pointers per node | 1 (`next`) | 2 (`next`, `prev`) |
| Memory per node | Lower | Higher (≈ 2x) |
| Forward traversal | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Backward traversal | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Deletion of given node (with pointer) | O(n) — needs prev | **O(1)** — direct via `prev` |
| Insertion before a given node | O(n) | **O(1)** |

