## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Analytical Matrix & Annotated C Implementation

### 3.1 Pointer Re-routing Derivations (The "Why" Behind 4-Link Updates)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Every insertion/deletion in a DLL requires updating **exactly 4 pointer links** in the worst case. Let's derive why.

Consider nodes **A**, **B**, and a **new node N** to be inserted between A and B:

$$
\text{Before insertion:} \quad A \xrightleftharpoons{} B
$$

$$
\text{(A.next} = B, \quad B.prev = A\text{)}
$$

After insertion, the structure must become:

$$
\text{After insertion:} \quad A \xrightleftharpoons{} N \xrightleftharpoons{} B
$$

For this transformation, the following **4 equations** must hold simultaneously:

$$
\begin{aligned}
N.prev &= A \\
N.next &= B \\
A.next &= N \\
B.prev &= N
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1 (save B reference):} \quad & \text{temp} = A.next \\
\text{Step 2 (link N backwards):} \quad & N.prev = A \\
\text{Step 3 (link N forwards):} \quad & N.next = \text{temp} \\
\text{Step 4 (link A forwards):} \quad & A.next = N \\
\text{Step 5 (link B backwards, if B exists):} \quad & \text{temp.prev} = N
\end{aligned}
$$

**Analytical Justification:** The order of Steps 1–3 is critical. If we naively set `A.next = N` **first**, we lose the reference to B (memory leak in pointer graph). Hence the convention is to **save old forward link first**, then build new links.

### 3.2 Boundary Condition Analysis Matrix

| Scenario | Insertion Logic | Deletion Logic |
|---|---|---|
| **Empty list** (HEAD = NULL) | Set HEAD = newNode; newNode->prev = NULL; newNode->next = NULL | Print "List Empty"; return |
| **Single node** | Same as empty case (becomes the only node) | HEAD = NULL; free(node) |
| **First node** | newNode->next = HEAD; HEAD->prev = newNode; HEAD = newNode | temp = HEAD; HEAD = HEAD->next; HEAD->prev = NULL; free(temp) |
| **Last node** | Traverse to last; newNode->prev = last; last->next = newNode; newNode->next = NULL | Traverse to last; last->prev->next = NULL; free(last) |
| **Middle node** | Standard 4-link update (see §3.1) | Standard 4-link update |

### 3.3 Complete Annotated C Implementation (KTU Lab Standard)

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

/* Step 1: Define the node structure */
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* prev;
    struct Node* next;
};

/* Global HEAD pointer (KTU lab convention) */
struct Node* head = NULL;

/* ---------- Helper: Create a new node ---------- */
struct Node* createNode(int value) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = value;
    newNode->prev = NULL;
    newNode->next = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

/* ---------- OPERATION 1: TRAVERSE (Forward) ---------- */
void traverse() {
    struct Node* temp = head;
    if (temp == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("DLL (forward): NULL <-> ");
    while (temp != NULL) {
        printf("%d <-> ", temp->data);
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    printf("NULL\n");
}

/* ---------- OPERATION 2: SEARCH ---------- */
int search(int key) {
    struct Node* temp = head;
    int position = 1;
    while (temp != NULL) {
        if (temp->data == key) {
            return position;   // Found at 'position'
        }
        temp = temp->next;
        position++;
    }
    return -1;   // Not found
}

/* ---------- OPERATION 3: INSERTION ---------- */

/* (a) Insert at beginning */
void insertAtBeginning(int value) {
    struct Node* newNode = createNode(value);
    if (head != NULL) {
        head->prev = newNode;   // Step 1: old head's prev points back
    }
    newNode->next = head;       // Step 2: new node's next points forward
    head = newNode;             // Step 3: update HEAD
}

/* (b) Insert at end */
void insertAtEnd(int value) {
    struct Node* newNode = createNode(value);
    if (head == NULL) {
        head = newNode;
        return;
    }
    struct Node* temp = head;
    while (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp = temp->next;     // Traverse to last node
    }
    temp->next = newNode;      // Link old last to new node
    newNode->prev = temp;      // Link new node back to old last
}

/* (c) Insert at given position (1-indexed) */
void insertAtPosition(int value, int pos) {
    if (pos == 1) {
        insertAtBeginning(value);
        return;
    }
    struct Node* temp = head;
    for (int i = 1; i < pos - 1 && temp != NULL; i++) {
        temp = temp->next;     // Reach node at (pos-1)
    }
    if (temp == NULL) {
        printf("Position out of range.\n");
        return;
    }
    struct Node* newNode = createNode(value);
    newNode->next = temp->next;   // Link new node forward
    newNode->prev = temp;         // Link new node backward
    if (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp->next->prev = newNode;  // Link next-node's prev back
    }
    temp->next = newNode;         // Link current node forward
}

/* ---------- OPERATION 4: DELETION ---------- */

/* (a) Delete from beginning */
void deleteFromBeginning() {
    if (head == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty. Nothing to delete.\n");
        return;
    }
    struct Node* temp = head;
    head = head->next;            // Move HEAD forward
    if (head != NULL) {
        head->prev = NULL;        // Detach old prev link
    }
    free(temp);                   // Free memory (avoid leak)
    printf("Deleted node from beginning.\n");
}

/* (b) Delete from end */
void deleteFromEnd() {
    if (head == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty. Nothing to delete.\n");
        return;
    }
    struct Node* temp = head;
    if (temp->next == NULL) {     // Only one node
        head = NULL;
        free(temp);
        return;
    }
    while (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp = temp->next;        // Reach last node
    }
    temp->prev->next = NULL;      // Second-last node's next = NULL
    free(temp);
    printf("Deleted node from end.\n");
}

/* (c) Delete from given position */
void deleteFromPosition(int pos) {
    if (head == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    if (pos == 1) {
        deleteFromBeginning();
        return;
    }
    struct Node* temp = head;
    for (int i = 1; i < pos && temp != NULL; i++) {
        temp = temp->next;        // Reach node at 'pos'
    }
    if (temp == NULL) {
        printf("Position out of range.\n");
        return;
    }
    if (temp->prev != NULL) {
        temp->prev->next = temp->next;   // Bypass temp from left
    }
    if (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp->next->prev = temp->prev;   // Bypass temp from right
    }
    free(temp);
    printf("Deleted node at position %d.\n", pos);
}

/* ---------- MAIN: DRIVER CODE ---------- */
int main() {
    int choice, value, pos, key;

    while (1) {
        printf("\n--- DLL OPERATIONS MENU ---\n");
        printf("1. Traverse\n2. Search\n3. Insert at Beginning\n");
        printf("4. Insert at End\n5. Insert at Position\n");
        printf("6. Delete from Beginning\n7. Delete from End\n");
        printf("8. Delete from Position\n9. Exit\n");
        printf("Enter choice: ");
        scanf("%d", &choice);

        switch (choice) {
            case 1: traverse(); break;
            case 2:
                printf("Enter key to search: "); scanf("%d", &key);
                pos = search(key);
                if (pos == -1) printf("Not found.\n");
                else printf("Found at position %d.\n", pos);
                break;
            case 3:
                printf("Enter value: "); scanf("%d", &value);
                insertAtBeginning(value); break;
            case 4:
                printf("Enter value: "); scanf("%d", &value);
                insertAtEnd(value); break;
            case 5:
                printf("Enter value and position: "); scanf("%d %d", &value, &pos);
                insertAtPosition(value, pos); break;
            case 6: deleteFromBeginning(); break;
            case 7: deleteFromEnd(); break;
            case 8:
                printf("Enter position: "); scanf("%d", &pos);
                deleteFromPosition(pos); break;
            case 9: exit(0);
            default: printf("Invalid choice.\n");
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

### 3.4 Sample Trace — Insertion at Position 2

Let initial list be: `NULL ⇄ 10 ⇄ 30 ⇄ NULL` and we insert **20 at position 2**.

| Step | Action | Pointer State |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `temp` traverses to position 1 (node with 10) | `temp → [10]` |
| 2 | `newNode = createNode(20)` | `newNode → [20, prev=?, next=?]` |
