## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

**Q1. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model Paper]**
*Define a Doubly Linked List. How does it differ from a Singly Linked List in terms of memory overhead and traversal capability?*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
A Doubly Linked List (DLL) is a linear data structure in which each node contains a data field and **two pointers** — one pointing to the **previous** node and one pointing to the **next** node, allowing traversal in **both directions** from any given node. In contrast, a **Singly Linked List (SLL)** contains only **one pointer** (`next`), permitting traversal in only the **forward direction**. As a result, a DLL consumes **more memory per node** (extra `prev` pointer) but enables **O(1) backward traversal** and **O(1) deletion of a known node** — operations that would require O(n) time in an SLL.

**Q2. [KTU University Exam – June 2024, Sample]**
*What is the time complexity of inserting a new node at the beginning of a doubly linked list? Justify.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
The time complexity is **O(1)** (constant time). Justification: Insertion at the beginning requires only three pointer operations — (1) `newNode->next = HEAD`, (2) `HEAD->prev = newNode` (if HEAD exists), and (3) `HEAD = newNode`. Since no traversal of the list is needed, the operation completes in a fixed number of steps regardless of the list size `n`, yielding O(1) time complexity.

