#### **Question B (14 Marks)** — *[Choice 2 — Alternative Set]*

**Q.B (a) [7 Marks]** Write a C program to insert a new node with value `x` at a **given position `pos`** in an existing doubly linked list. Handle all edge cases: position = 1, position > length, and empty list.

**Model Solution:**

```c
void insertAtPosition(int x, int pos) {
    /* Case 1: Empty list — only valid if pos == 1 */
    if (head == NULL) {
        if (pos != 1) {
            printf("Invalid position for empty list.\n");
            return;
        }
        struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
        newNode->data = x;
        newNode->prev = NULL;
        newNode->next = NULL;
        head = newNode;
        return;
    }

    /* Case 2: Insert at beginning */
    if (pos == 1) {
        struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
        newNode->data = x;
        newNode->prev = NULL;
        newNode->next = head;
        head->prev = newNode;
        head = newNode;
        return;
    }

    /* Case 3: Insert at middle or end */
    struct Node* temp = head;
    for (int i = 1; i < pos - 1 && temp != NULL; i++) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    if (temp == NULL) {
        printf("Position out of range.\n");
        return;
    }

    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = x;
    newNode->next = temp->next;       /* Step 1: link forward */
    newNode->prev = temp;             /* Step 2: link backward */

    if (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp->next->prev = newNode;   /* Step 3: fix next node's prev */
    }
    temp->next = newNode;             /* Step 4: fix current node's next */
}
```

**Mark Distribution (7 marks):**
- Edge case handling (empty list, pos=1) (2 marks)
- Traversal to (pos-1) (1 mark)
- 4-link pointer update (3 marks)
- Position validation (1 mark)

**Q.B (b) [7 Marks]** Write a C function to delete the node at a given position `pos` from a doubly linked list. Free the deleted node's memory. Show the working with an example list `10 ⇄ 20 ⇄ 30 ⇄ 40` deleting position 2.

**Model Solution:**

```c
void deleteAtPosition(int pos) {
    if (head == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty.\n");
        return;
    }

    struct Node* temp = head;

    /* Traverse to node at 'pos' */
    for (int i = 1; i < pos && temp != NULL; i++) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    if (temp == NULL) {
        printf("Position out of range.\n");
        return;
    }

    /* Update prev node's next pointer */
    if (temp->prev != NULL) {
        temp->prev->next = temp->next;
    } else {
        head = temp->next;   /* Deleting first node */
    }

    /* Update next node's prev pointer */
    if (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp->next->prev = temp->prev;
    }

    free(temp);   /* Free memory — critical for no memory leak */
    printf("Deleted node at position %d.\n", pos);
}
```

**Working Trace (List: 10 ⇄ 20 ⇄ 30 ⇄ 40, Delete pos = 2):**

| Step | Action | Resulting List |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `temp` reaches node `20` | `temp → [20]` |
| 2 | `temp->prev->next = temp->next` | `10.next → [30]` |
| 3 | `temp->next->prev = temp->prev` | `30.prev → [10]` |
| 4 | `free(temp)` | `10 ⇄ 30 ⇄ 40` |

**Final List:** `10 ⇄ 30 ⇄ 40` ✅

**Mark Distribution (7 marks):**
- Traversal logic (1 mark)
- `prev` link update (2 marks)
- `next` link update (2 marks)
- `free()` call and edge cases (2 marks)

