> [!TIP]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — Read this 5 minutes before the exam!**

- ✅ **DLL Node Anatomy:** `data` + `prev` + `next` — **3 fields, 2 pointers**.
- ✅ **HEAD** points to the first node; the last node's `next = NULL`; the first node's `prev = NULL`.
- ✅ **Insertion requires updating 4 links** in the worst case (vs. 2 in SLL).
- ✅ **Order of pointer updates is critical** — save old forward link FIRST, then rewire.
- ✅ **Deletion must include `free()`** — examiners actively check for this.
- ✅ **Boundary conditions to always handle:**
  - `head == NULL` (empty list)
  - Single-node list
  - Deletion/insertion at head (pos = 1)
  - Deletion/insertion at tail
  - Position out of valid range
- ✅ **Time Complexities to memorize:**
  - Insertion at beginning: **O(1)**
  - Insertion at end (no tail pointer): **O(n)**
  - Search: **O(n)**
  - Deletion of a known-node pointer: **O(1)** ⭐ (key DLL advantage)
- ✅ **Use a `TAIL` pointer** to make end-operations O(1) — common viva question.
- ✅ **Reverse traversal:** Start from tail, follow `prev` pointers — unique DLL feature.
- ✅ **Memory Overhead:** DLL uses **2 pointers per node**; SLL uses 1 — trade-off for bidirectional access.
- ✅ **Real-world applications:** Browser history, LRU cache, undo/redo, text editor cursors, OS process scheduling (Linux kernel `list_head`).

