## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

A **polynomial** $P(x)$ of degree $n$ is a mathematical expression of the form:

$$P(x) = a_n x^n + a_{n-1} x^{n-1} + \dots + a_1 x^1 + a_0 x^0$$

where each $a_i$ is called the **coefficient** and the non-negative integer $i$ is called the **exponent** (or power) of the corresponding term. The term $a_0$ is known as the **constant term**.

In the **Linked List Representation** of a polynomial, each term of the polynomial is stored as a **node** in a singly (or doubly) linked list. Every node contains three fields:

| Field | Symbol | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| Coefficient | `coeff` | Stores the numerical value $a_i$ |
| Exponent | `expo` | Stores the power $i$ |
| Link / Next | `next` | Pointer to the next term-node |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Convention**: Polynomials are stored in **descending order of exponents** (highest degree first) so that polynomial addition can be performed in a **single linear traversal**, exactly mirroring the way we read/write them by hand.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy (The "Train of Terms" Intuition)

Imagine a **freight train** where each **wagon (node)** carries exactly **one labelled box** containing a term of the polynomial.

- The **wagon number painted on the box** = the exponent (e.g., the box on Wagon 3 carries $x^3$).
- The **weight inside the box** = the coefficient (e.g., weight $5$ means $5x^3$).
- The **coupling chain** = the `next` pointer linking one wagon to the next.
- **Empty wagons (terms with coefficient 0) are simply not attached** to the train — we never waste memory on a term that contributes nothing to the polynomial.
- **Combining two trains (polynomials)** is done by walking along both trains simultaneously: if both have a wagon with the same number, we **merge the weights**; otherwise, the **wagon with the larger number goes first** into the result train.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why linked list and not array?** Because real-world polynomials are **sparse** — a polynomial of degree 1000 may have only 5 non-zero terms. An array would force you to allocate 1001 slots, wasting **~99.5% of memory**. A linked list uses **exactly as many nodes as there are non-zero terms**, achieving **optimal space complexity of $O(k)$** where $k$ is the number of non-zero terms.

### 1.3 Standard Metrics Used

- **Degree of polynomial**: Highest exponent present, denoted $\deg(P)$.
- **Number of non-zero terms**: Length of the linked list, denoted $n$.
- **Space per node**: **3 units** (one `int` coefficient + one `int` exponent + one pointer, typically **12 bytes** on a 32-bit system or **16 bytes** on a 64-bit system).

