## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

**Q1. [KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**
*Why are polynomials represented using linked lists instead of arrays? List any two advantages.*

**Model Answer (3 marks)**:
A polynomial of degree $n$ may have far fewer than $n+1$ non-zero terms (sparse polynomial). An array representation allocates $n+1$ contiguous memory slots, leading to **wastage of memory** for missing terms. A linked list, on the other hand, creates **one node per non-zero term**, so memory usage is proportional to the number of non-zero terms. Two advantages are: (1) **Optimal space utilization** for sparse polynomials — $O(k)$ instead of $O(n)$. (2) **Dynamic size** — adding or removing terms is an $O(1)$ pointer operation, no shifting required as in arrays. (1 mark for stating array limitation, 1 mark for linked list benefit, 1 mark for second advantage).

**Q2. [KTU University Exam — June 2024]**
*What is the time complexity of adding two polynomials represented as sorted linked lists? Justify your answer.*

**Model Answer (3 marks)**:
The time complexity of polynomial addition using sorted linked lists is $O(n + m)$, where $n$ and $m$ are the number of non-zero terms in the two polynomials. (1 mark). Justification: The algorithm performs a **single linear pass** through both lists, advancing one or both pointers at each step, without any nested loops or backtracking (1 mark). In the worst case, every node of both lists is visited exactly once, leading to $O(n + m)$ (1 mark).

