## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

A **Binary Search Tree (BST)** is a node-based, non-linear hierarchical data structure in which each node contains a **key (data)** and at most **two child nodes** — a *left child* and a *right child*. The defining **BST Invariant Property** states that for every node `N`:

$$\text{All keys in } N\text{.leftSubtree} \;<\; N\text{.key} \;<\; \text{All keys in } N\text{.rightSubtree}$$

This recursive ordering property enables efficient **searching, insertion, and deletion** in **O(h)** time, where `h` is the height of the tree. In a balanced BST, `h = O(log n)`; in a degenerate (skewed) BST, `h = O(n)`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Board Definition to Memorize:**
> "A Binary Search Tree is a binary tree such that for each node, all elements in the left subtree are less than the node, and all elements in the right subtree are greater than the node. This property holds recursively for every subtree."

> [!NOTE]
> **Self-Balancing vs Standard BST:** The KTU syllabus (PCITL308) covers the *standard* (unbalanced) BST. AVL/Red-Black trees are part of the Algorithms course (PCCST401/PCS403), not this lab experiment.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The Dictionary Lookup

Imagine a physical **English dictionary**:
- You don't scan every word linearly to find "Mango".
- You flip to the **middle**, compare, and decide: go **left** (words before) or **right** (words after).
- You repeat the halving on the chosen half.

A BST works **exactly the same way** — the **root is the midpoint**, the **left subtree contains smaller keys**, and the **right subtree contains larger keys**. Every comparison **eliminates half of the remaining candidates**, giving logarithmic performance.

### 1.3 Standard Metrics & Properties

- **Maximum nodes** at level `l` (root at level 0): **2^l**
- **Total nodes** in a tree of height `h`: between **h + 1** (skewed) and **2^(h+1) − 1** (perfect)
- **Minimum height** for `n` nodes: **⌊log₂(n)⌋**
- **In-order traversal** of a BST always produces keys in **strictly ascending sorted order** — this is the cornerstone property used in validation and sorting (Tree Sort).

