## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Structural Anatomy of a BST Node

A BST node in C contains three fields:

| Field | Type | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `data` | `int` (or generic `void*`) | The key/value stored in the node |
| `left` | `struct Node*` | Pointer to the left child (smaller keys) |
| `right` | `struct Node*` | Pointer to the right child (larger keys) |

### 2.2 The Four Core Operations — Logic Breakdown

#### 2.2.1 Creation
- **Why:** A BST must be initialised before use; the typical approach is creating an *empty tree* (root = `NULL`) and then inserting nodes one at a time.
- **How:** `root = NULL;` — the tree is logically empty. Each subsequent `insert()` call grows the tree.

#### 2.2.2 Insertion (The "Find-Your-Spot" Algorithm)
- **Step 1:** Start at the **root**.
- **Step 2:** If the new key is **less** than the current node, **go left**; if **greater**, **go right**.
- **Step 3:** If you reach a `NULL` pointer, that is the insertion point — **create the new node here**.
- **Step 4:** If the key equals an existing node, **do not insert duplicates** (return unchanged or handle per specification).
- **Why:** This preserves the BST invariant in O(h) time.

#### 2.2.3 Search (Recursive and Iterative)
- **Recursive:** Compare target with root; recurse into the appropriate subtree; return `NULL` on miss.
- **Iterative:** Loop downward using two pointers (current + parent); avoids stack overhead.
- **Why:** In a balanced BST, each comparison halves the search space → **O(log n)**.

#### 2.2.4 Deletion (The Three-Case Problem)
Deletion is the **most examiner-favoured** operation in KTU papers. Three cases arise based on the node to be deleted:

| Case | Condition | Action |
|---|---|---|
| **Case 0** | Node has **no children** (leaf) | Simply remove the node; set parent's child link to `NULL` |
| **Case 1** | Node has **exactly one child** | Replace the node with its only child |
| **Case 2** | Node has **two children** | Replace node's key with its **in-order successor** (smallest in right subtree) **OR in-order predecessor** (largest in left subtree), then recursively delete that successor/predecessor |

> [!NOTE]
> **Why the in-order successor/predecessor?** Because the successor is the **smallest key greater than the deleted key** — replacing with it maintains the BST ordering invariant on both sides of the new position.

### 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Metric / Operation | Average Case | Worst Case (Skewed) | Best Case (Perfect) |
|---|---|---|---|
| Search | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(\log n)$ |
| Insertion | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(\log n)$ |
| Deletion | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(\log n)$ |
| Space (n nodes) | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ |
| Height of balanced BST | — | — | $\lfloor \log_2 n \rfloor$ |
| Min nodes for height $h$ | $h + 1$ | $h + 1$ | $h + 1$ |
| Max nodes for height $h$ | $2^{h+1} - 1$ | $2^{h+1} - 1$ | $2^{h+1} - 1$ |

### 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Database Indexing:** B-trees (a generalised BST variant) power MySQL InnoDB indexes.
- **Auto-complete / Spell Checkers:** Tries and BSTs store sorted dictionaries.
- **File Systems:** HFS+, NTFS, ext4 use B-trees for directory indexing.
- **Compiler Symbol Tables:** BSTs store identifiers with their scope/type information.
- **Network Routing:** Longest-prefix matching uses modified BSTs.
- **In-memory sort:** **Tree Sort** uses BST + in-order traversal in $O(n \log n)$ average time.

