## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, May 2024]`**
**State and explain the BST property. Why is in-order traversal of a BST always sorted?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
- **(1 mark) BST Property:** For every node `N`, all keys in `N`'s left subtree are strictly less than `N.key`, and all keys in `N`'s right subtree are strictly greater than `N.key`. This property holds recursively.
- **(1 mark) In-order logic:** In-order traversal visits `Left → Root → Right`. By the BST property, the left subtree contains only smaller keys, the root is the pivot, and the right subtree contains only larger keys. Recursively applying this yields a sorted sequence.
- **(1 mark) Example:** For BST `50, 30, 70`, in-order yields `30, 50, 70` — sorted ascending.

---

**Q2. `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2022]`**
**Compare the time complexity of search operation in a balanced BST and a skewed BST. Justify.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
- **(1 mark) Balanced BST:** Height $h = O(\log n)$, so search is $O(\log n)$.
- **(1 mark) Skewed BST:** Behaves like a linked list; height $h = O(n)$, so search is $O(n)$.
- **(1 mark) Justification:** Each comparison in a BST eliminates one subtree. In a balanced tree, the subtree sizes are halved at each step (logarithmic), whereas in a skewed tree, only one child is eliminated per step (linear). Example: inserting `1, 2, 3, 4, 5` in order produces a right-skewed tree.

---

