#### **Model Solution for Q.A(b):**

**Algorithm — Recursive Insert:**

```c
struct Node* insert(struct Node *root, int value) {
    /* Base case: empty spot found */
    if (root == NULL)
        return createNode(value);

    /* Recursive descent: preserve BST invariant */
    if (value < root->data)
        root->left  = insert(root->left,  value);
    else if (value > root->data)
        root->right = insert(root->right, value);

    /* Unchanged root pointer returned to parent */
    return root;
}
```

**Explanation (mark-wise):**

- **(2 marks)** Base case: when `root == NULL`, the new node is created and returned as the local subtree root.
- **(2 marks)** Recursive case: the algorithm descends either left (smaller key) or right (larger key), recursively attaching the new node to the appropriate `NULL` slot. The recursive call's return value is re-assigned to `root->left` or `root->right`, ensuring the parent pointer is correctly updated.
- **(2 marks)** Invariant preservation: because we always descend in the direction dictated by the BST property (smaller left, larger right), the resulting tree automatically satisfies: `left < root < right` for every node.
- **(1 mark)** Complexity: $O(h)$ where $h$ is the tree height; in a balanced BST, $h = O(\log n)$ giving $O(\log n)$ average; in a skewed BST, $h = O(n)$ giving worst-case $O(n)$.

