### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember (Rapid-Revision Checklist)

> [!NOTE]
> **High-Density Revision Summary — Read before every BST exam:**

- **BST Property:** `Left < Node < Right`, recursive for every subtree.
- **In-order traversal of a BST = sorted ascending sequence** (most powerful property for validation).
- **Insertion:** Find the `NULL` spot by descending left/right, then attach the new node. **Duplicates are usually ignored.**
- **Search:** Descend left/right based on comparison; $O(\log n)$ average, $O(n)$ worst case.
- **Deletion has 3 cases:**
  - **Case 0 (Leaf):** Just remove it.
  - **Case 1 (One Child):** Bypass the node with its only child.
  - **Case 2 (Two Children):** Replace with **in-order successor** (or predecessor), then recursively delete that successor.
- **All operations** (insert, search, delete) take $O(h)$ time where $h$ = height of the tree.
- **Worst case** = sorted insertion sequence → produces a **skewed tree** with $h = n$.
- **Best case** = balanced BST with $h = \lfloor \log_2 n \rfloor$.
- **Memory layout:** Each node = `data + left pointer + right pointer`; dynamically allocated using `malloc`.
- **No self-balancing** in standard BST (AVL/Red-Black come later in PCCST401 / Algorithm courses).
- **Time complexity table** (must memorise for KTU): Search/Insert/Delete → $O(\log n)$ avg, $O(n)$ worst.
- **Lab Viva Questions:** *"What happens if you insert a pre-sorted sequence?"* (Answer: Skewed tree, $O(n)$ operations). *"How do you validate a BST?"* (Answer: In-order traversal must be strictly ascending).
- **Common function signatures to memorise:** `insert(Node*, int)`, `search(Node*, int)`, `deleteNode(Node*, int)`, `findMin(Node*)`, `inorder/preorder/postorder(Node*)`.

