# 🌳 SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

A **Tree** is a non-linear, hierarchical data structure consisting of nodes connected by edges. It is formally defined as a finite set $T$ of one or more nodes such that there is one designated node called the **root**, and the remaining nodes are partitioned into $n \geq 0$ disjoint subsets $T_1, T_2, \ldots, T_n$, each of which is itself a tree (recursive definition).

In the context of **KTU PCITL308 – Module Experiment 2 ("Any application program using trees")**, students are expected to implement a complete, end-to-end application using one of the following tree variants:

| Tree Variant | Typical KTU Lab Application |
|---|---|
| **Binary Search Tree (BST)** | Dictionary / Phonebook / Student Record Search |
| **Expression Tree** | Infix expression evaluator using postfix conversion |
| **AVL Tree** | Self-balancing dictionary |
| **Heap** | Priority queue / Heap sort |
| **Huffman Tree** | Data compression (text encoding) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Scheme Lab Evaluation Focus:** The examiner checks for (1) correct node structure with dynamic memory allocation, (2) working menu-driven program, (3) all required operations, (4) proper use of recursion for traversals, and (5) accurate viva-voce explanation. A program that compiles and runs correctly scores full marks.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy – "Why Trees?"

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-world analogy – The Family Tree / Organization Chart:** Imagine a family tree. The eldest ancestor is the **root**. Their children are **child nodes**, grandchildren are at the next level, and so on. Just as you can search for a particular descendant by following a path from the root, computer scientists use trees to **search, sort, and represent hierarchical data** with logarithmic time complexity $O(\log n)$ in balanced cases — vastly faster than scanning an array of $n$ elements at $O(n)$.

**Another analogy — The Decision Tree:** Every "yes/no" question splits a problem into smaller sub-problems, forming branches. This is exactly how a **Binary Search Tree** stores data — each comparison decides whether to go *left* (smaller values) or *right* (larger values).

## 1.3 Key Terminology (Mandatory for Viva)

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **Root** | Topmost node with no parent |
| **Leaf** | Node with no children |
| **Internal Node** | Node with at least one child |
| **Degree of a Node** | Number of children of that node |
| **Height of Tree** | Longest path from root to a leaf |
| **Depth of Node** | Distance from root to that node |
| **Subtree** | A node plus all its descendants |
| **Edge** | Connection between parent and child |

> [!NOTE]
> **Syllabus Highlight:** For **Expression Trees**, the **in-order traversal always yields the original infix expression** (with appropriate parenthesization). For **BSTs**, the **in-order traversal always yields a sorted sequence** of keys.

