# 🧠 SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Two Most Tested KTU Tree Applications

### 🔹 APPLICATION A: Expression Tree (Evaluator)

An **Expression Tree** is a binary tree where:
- **Leaf nodes** → operands (numbers/variables)
- **Internal nodes** → operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `^`)

**Construction strategy** used in KTU labs:
1. Convert the **infix expression** → **postfix expression** using a stack (Shunting-Yard / Edsger Dijkstra algorithm).
2. Read the postfix expression left-to-right using a stack of *tree node pointers*:
   - If token is an **operand** → create a node, push onto stack.
   - If token is an **operator** → pop two nodes (right first, then left), make them children of a new operator node, push the new node.

### 🔹 APPLICATION B: Binary Search Tree (Dictionary)

A **BST** is a binary tree where for every node $N$:
$$\text{All keys in } N\text{.left} < N.\text{key} < \text{All keys in } N.\text{right}$$

**Standard operations** in a KTU dictionary program:
- `insert(key)` — places new node in correct BST position
- `search(key)` — recursive or iterative lookup
- `delete(key)` — handles **3 cases**: leaf, one child, two children (replace with inorder successor)
- `inorder()` — prints sorted dictionary
- `preorder()` / `postorder()` — for displaying structure

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> Memorize this table — these complexities are asked directly in viva and Part A questions.

| Operation | Average Case (Balanced) | Worst Case (Skewed) | Tree Type |
|---|---|---|---|
| Search | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | BST |
| Insert | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | BST |
| Delete | $O(\log n)$ | $O(n)$ | BST |
| Inorder Traversal | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ | Any Binary Tree |
| Build Expression Tree | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ | Expression Tree |
| Evaluate Expression Tree | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ | Expression Tree |
| Heapify (per node) | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ | Heap |
| AVL Insert (with rotations) | $O(\log n)$ | $O(\log n)$ | AVL |
| Huffman Code Generation | $O(n \log n)$ | $O(n \log n)$ | Huffman Tree |

### Key Mathematical Properties

For a binary tree with $n$ nodes:
$$n = n_0 + n_1 + n_2$$
$$E = n - 1 \quad \text{(edges in any tree)}$$
$$n_2 = n_0 - 1 \quad \text{(relation: internal nodes with 2 children)}$$

Where:
- $n_0$ = number of leaf nodes
- $n_1$ = number of nodes with exactly 1 child
- $n_2$ = number of nodes with exactly 2 children
- $E$ = number of edges

**Height relationships:**
$$h_{\min} = \lfloor \log_2 n \rfloor \quad \text{(for a complete binary tree)}$$
$$h_{\max} = n - 1 \quad \text{(for a skewed tree — worst case)}$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Engineering Utility:** BSTs power database indexing (B+ trees are generalizations), Expression Trees are used in compilers to evaluate and optimize arithmetic expressions, Heaps are used in OS process schedulers and Dijkstra's shortest path algorithm, and Huffman trees form the backbone of file compression formats like ZIP, JPEG, and MP3.

